abstract = {Neural engineering, itself an 'emerging interdisciplinary research area' [1] hasundergone a sea change over the past few years with the emergence of excitingnew optical technologies for monitoring, stimulating, inhibiting and, moregenerally, modulating neural activity. To a large extent, this change is driven bythe realization of the promise and complementary strengths that emergingphoto-stimulation tools offer to add to the neural engineer's toolbox, which hasbeen almost exclusively based on electrical stimulation technologies. Notably,photo-stimulation is non-contact, can in some cases be genetically targeted tospecific cell populations, can achieve high spatial specificity (cellular or evensub-cellular) in two or three dimensions, and opens up the possibility oflarge-scale spatial-temporal patterned stimulation. It also offers a seamlesssolution to the problem of cross-talk generated by simultaneous electricalstimulation and recording.},
